snippet: The country made it clear it feared it was being sucked into an effort to “interfere in electoral processes” in the United States....
abstract: Ecuador cuts off internet access to Julian Assange, Wikileaks founder exiled in country's London embassy, citing fears of being involved by proxy in activities that could interfere with United States presidential election; announcement comes shortly after organization's leak of speeches Hillary Clinton delivered to Goldman Sachs.

byline.original: By STEVEN ERLANGER and DAVID E. SANGER
byline.contributor: Steven Erlanger reported from London, and David E. Sanger from Washington. Nicholas Casey contributed reporting from Caracas, Venezuela.

lead_paragraph: The country made it clear it feared it was being sucked into an effort to “interfere in electoral processes” in the United States.

headline.main: Ecuador Cuts Internet of Julian Assange, WikiLeaks’ Founder
headline.print_headline: Ecuador Cuts Assange’s Link to the Internet
